 6.1 Einstein‚Äôs Static Universe Shortly after completing the general theory of relativity, Einstein went on to apply his new theory to the universe as a whole !! The structure of the universe beyond our Milky Way galaxy was then completely unknown, thus Einstein made some assumptions. Einstein assumed that the universe is isotropic on average. (It looks more or less the same in all directions). We now know that if the distribution of galaxies is smoothed over distances of 300 million light years or so, it does appear to be homogeneous and isotropic. The universe cannot be homogeneous and isotropic unless space itself has these properties and thus, the curvature of space should be (on average) the same at all places and in all directions. As discussed earlier there are only 3 types of such spaces: a flat Euclidean space, a closed spherical space, and an open hyperbolic space. Einstein also assumed that the average characteristics of the universe, such as the average density of stars, do not change with time. But as it turns out the equations of General Relativity have no solutions with these properties. The problem is that masses distributed in the universe are pulled together by gravity and refuse to stay at rest. The theory was suggesting that the universe couldn‚Äôt be static. Einstein said that the equations for General Relativity had to be modified to endow vacuum. As per these modified equations the energy density \(ho_{
